Yi et al. prepared the aluminum oxide (Al2O3)-coated MWCNTs material through the sol-gel method and then added it to an epoxy coating [91]. According to the SEM images of MWCNTs and cladding MWCNTs (Fig. 20
                           ), the MWCNTs before being coated showed a clear tubular structure tangled together to their high surface energy. The MWCNTs, after being coated, represented the ‘‘honeycomb’’ structure with a layer of material on the surface of MWCNTs, which caused a reduction in the surface energy of MWCNTs. The electrochemical investigations indicated that the pure epoxy coating ultimately failed after 96 h exposure to the corrosive media. The electrolyte solution just permeated into the MWCNTs/epoxy coating reached the coating/metal interface. There was no severe change in the Al2O3-coated MWCNTs/epoxy composite coating, indicating its superior corrosion protection action (Fig. 21
                           ). However, the presence of a layer of Al2O3 affected the flexibility of composite coating negatively, and the wear resistance of the Al2O3-coated MWCNTs/epoxy composite coating was also improved in comparison with MWCNTs/epoxy.

Ramezanzadeh et al. successfully functionalized GO nanosheets' surface with p-phenylenediamine (P) by chemical bonding between the carboxylic and epoxide groups of GO and amine groups of diamine [120]. As a consequence of functionalization, the surface of GO found hydrophobic characteristics resulting in better dispersion and barrier properties in the epoxy matrix compared to the GO nanosheets. The FGO incorporation considerably enhanced the corrosion protection properties of the epoxy coating (see Fig. 31
                              ). Results obviously confirmed that FGO nanosheets provided a higher degree of coating protection rather than GO ones. Moreover, it can be seen that shift of the breakpoint frequency, fb, values (adversely related to the coating delamination from the substrate) to higher frequencies for the EP and EP/0.1 wt.% GO samples were more than EP/0.1 wt.% FGO sample with the elapsed immersion time which indicates that the barrier performance of the EP enhanced distinctly with FGO. Furthermore, the FGO filled coating possessed the lowest damage and delamination degrees due to less corrosive electrolyte diffusion into the coating bulk. As illustrated in Fig. 32
                              , FGO nanosheets were also able to increase the coating's ionic resistance by their earned negative charges in the alkaline environment. Negatively charged FGO could adsorb cations selectively and prevent the anions from diffusing into the epoxy coating. So that, less amount of Cl− anions was capable of diffusing in the coating as long as it was negatively charged, resulting in lower hydrolytic degradation of the coating.

Ma et al. synthesized graphene oxide decorated with silica nanoparticles in the presence of 3-aminopropyltriethoxysilane (APTS) and 3-glycidoxypropyltrimethoxysilane (GPTS) [128]. As illustrated schematically in Fig. 38
                           , the surface of GO and silica were functionalized with GPTS and APTS, respectively, then SiO2–GO hybrids prepared through the chemical bonding of the GO functional groups and silane coupling agents. The TEM images of obtained SiO2–GO hybrids (Fig. 39
                           ) confirmed the decoration of spherical nanoparticles on the GO nanosheets with monolayer structure and without aggregation. SiO2–GO hybrid exhibited far better dispersion than GO nanosheets and SiO2 nanoparticles within the epoxy resin, resulting in the coating's superior anticorrosive performance. Yu et al. also fabricated GO-Al2O3 and TiO2-GO hybrids using APTS as a coupling agent, capable of incorporating sheet-like structures within an epoxy coating [129].
